2023-10-03

1. Introduction

Business Problem

In the ever-competitive grocery market, ensuring that marketing campaigns and promotions not only reach the target audience but also compel them to make purchases is crucial. Regork, a national grocery chain, employs various marketing campaigns and promotions to enhance its market reach and elevate sales. However, the effectiveness of these campaigns and their genuine impact on purchasing behaviors among diverse customer segments remain intricate puzzles.

Objective

The objective of our analysis is to unravel the nuances of marketing and campaign effectiveness by exploring the relationship between promotional activities, customer demographics, and purchasing behaviors. We intend to delve into questions such as:

  • Which campaigns have demonstrated substantial influence on purchasing?
  • Are there specific customer demographics that are more responsive to particular campaigns or promotions?
  • What products are most often purchased under promotional campaigns?
  • Is there a noticeable uplift in sales during and after campaigns?

Significance

Understanding the dynamics of campaign effectiveness allows Regork to:

  1. Allocate marketing budget more judiciously, maximizing ROI.
  2. Tailor future campaigns to be more resonant with specific customer segments.
  3. Identify and optimize the timing, duration, and featured products of campaigns.
  4. Enhance customer engagement and satisfaction by offering relevant promotions.

Methodology

To navigate through this, we will:

  1. Merge transactional data with campaign and product information, creating a consolidated view of customer purchases in relation to promotional campaigns.
  2. Perform exploratory data analysis to identify patterns, anomalies, or trends in purchasing behavior during campaigns.
  3. Explore customer demographics to understand who is most influenced by campaigns.
  4. Evaluate the impact of promotions on sales volumes during and post-campaign periods.

Implications

Our analysis will pave the way to:

  • Forge data-driven marketing strategies that amplify sales and customer engagement.
  • Identify opportunities to enhance campaign effectiveness, targeting, and timing.
  • Recognize potential areas for growth and further investment in specific product categories or customer segments.

Data Import and Cleaning

Transactions Data Cleaning

clean_data <- function(data, required_cols){
  data %>%
    select(all_of(required_cols)) %>%
    filter(across(all_of(required_cols), ~!is.na(.))) %>%
    distinct()
}


selected_transactions <- clean_data(transactions, c("household_id", "product_id", "store_id", "quantity", "sales_value", "week", "retail_disc", "coupon_disc", "coupon_match_disc"))
selected_products <- clean_data(products, c("manufacturer_id", "product_id", "department", "product_category", "product_type"))
selected_campaigns <- clean_data(campaigns, c("campaign_id", "household_id"))
selected_coupons <- clean_data(coupons, c("campaign_id", "product_id", "coupon_upc"))
selected_coupon_redemptions <- clean_data(coupon_redemptions, c("campaign_id", "household_id", "coupon_upc","redemption_date"))
selected_demographics <- clean_data(demographics, c("age", "household_id", "income","marital_status","household_size"))



dt_selected_transactions <- as.data.table(selected_transactions)
dt_selected_transactions[, campaign_cost := abs(retail_disc) + abs(coupon_disc) + abs(coupon_match_disc)]
dt_selected_transactions[, net_profit := sales_value - 0.5 * sales_value - campaign_cost]
dt_selected_coupons <- as.data.table(selected_coupons)
dt_selected_campaigns <- as.data.table(selected_campaigns)
dt_selected_coupon_redemptions <- as.data.table(selected_coupon_redemptions)
dt_selected_demographics <- as.data.table(selected_demographics)
dt_selected_campaign_descriptions <- as.data.table(campaign_descriptions)

top_transactions_plot <- ggplot(top_campaigns, aes(x = reorder(campaign_type, -total_transactions), y = total_transactions, fill = as.factor(campaign_type))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", show.legend = FALSE) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Pastel1") +
  labs(title = "performance Campaigns with Coupons",
       x = "Campaign Type", 
       y = "Total Transactions") +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_text(aes(label = scales::dollar(total_transactions)),
            vjust = -0.5,
            col = "black",
            size = 3.5) +
  geom_point(aes(x = reorder(campaign_type, -total_transactions), y = total_transactions), 
             color = "black", size = 3, show.legend = FALSE) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16),  # Title settings
    axis.title.x = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12),  # X-axis label settings
    axis.title.y = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12)  # Y-axis label settings
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::dollar)

Summary

1. Campaigns Impact on Purchases

  1. Top/Bottom Performing Campaigns with Coupons
  • Top Performing Campaign with Coupons: Campaign 5 (Total Sales: $82,600.86, Avg Sales/Transaction: $3.87)
  • Least Performing Campaign with Coupons: Campaign 24 (Total Sales: NA)
  1. Top/Bottom Performing Campaigns without Coupons
  • Top Performing Campaign without Coupons: Campaign 5 (Total Sales: $138,418.59, Avg Sales/Transaction: $3.32)
  • Least Performing Campaign without Coupons: Campaign 24 (Total Sales: NA)

Recommendations:

  • Optimize Top Performing Campaigns: Further analysis on why campaign 5 is successful (customer demographics, offered products, etc.) could provide insights to replicate its success.
  • Investigate Low/Non-Performing Campaigns: Understanding why campaign 24 (and others) did not perform well or have no sales will highlight areas for improvement or avoidance in future campaigns.

2. Demographics Impact on Purchases

  1. Transactions with Coupons
  • Age groups 45-54 and 35-44 show high total sales across various income brackets and campaign types.
  1. Transactions without Coupons
  • Again, age groups 45-54 and 35-44 dominate in sales, indicating they are key demographics.

Recommendations:

  • Target Key Demographics: Tailor campaigns to age groups 45-54 and 35-44, as they tend to generate higher sales.

  • Diversify Offerings: Develop strategies to engage other age and income demographics to diversify customer base and increase sales.

3. ROI Analysis

  • Campaigns 5 and 4 exhibit notable ROI with coupons, indicating a successful balancing of costs and sales.
  • Without coupons, campaigns 5 and 4 again stand out in ROI, suggesting efficacy in different promotional contexts.

Recommendations:

  • ROI-Focused Strategy: Use data from campaigns 5 and 4 to model future campaigns, optimizing for highest ROI.
  • Cost Efficiency: Review high-cost campaigns to ensure they provide adequate return and adjust as needed.

4. Conversion Rate

  • There’s a wide range of conversion rates, from around 6% to 13%, depending on the campaign.

Recommendations:

  • Enhance Conversion: Identify strategies from high-conversion campaigns (e.g., 13%) to enhance those with lower conversions.
  • Customer Journey Analysis: Investigate the customer journey in high-converting campaigns and implement successful strategies across others.

Additional Strategic Recommendations:

  1. Seasonality Analysis: Analyze purchase trends to understand seasonal impacts on sales and tailor campaigns accordingly.

  2. Multi-Channel Approach: Employ various channels (email, SMS, app notifications) to engage customers based on their preferred communication medium.

  3. Competitive Analysis: Keep an eye on competitors’ strategies and ensure your campaigns offer something unique or better value.

  4. Product Bundling: Use data to identify products that are commonly purchased together and create bundled offers.

Closing Thoughts:

It’s imperative to continually analyze data post-campaign and adjust strategies accordingly. The above recommendations provide a structured approach, but the dynamic nature of consumer behavior necessitates flexibility and adaptability in strategies. Always keep the customer at the center of decision-making and strive to deliver value in a way that also aligns with business objectives.
